      <byline class="print_byline">By Barry Bearak (NYT)</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Bearak, Barry</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Court proceedings begin in Kabul for eight foreign relief workers, including two Americans, charged with preaching Christianity; neither the accused, their relatives nor press are allowed in court (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>A month after eight foreign relief workers, including two Americans, were arrested on charges of preaching Christianity, court proceedings began in Kabul, though neither the accused, their relatives nor the press have been allowed in court. Fifteen Islamic clerics are reviewing the evidence, said Chief Justice Noor Muhammad Saqib. Details of the legal procedures are still being worked out. It remains to be seen whether the defendants will be permitted to testify or allowed use of lawyers, Justice Saqib said.</p>
        <p>Barry Bearak (NYT)</p>
      </block>
